passages.name: 7b
passages.text:
I stand on the dock. Snow coming down hard, just beginning to stick. The dogs sniffing around the woodpile. No one else.

Waves in Big Sand Lake churning.

I wait<<replace "...">>

...then a great blue heron flies past the dock, traversing the inlet. First in a slow glide. But then she beats her wings, and that's all I can hear. Air-Pusher glad that the summer speedboats are gone.<<endreplace>>

A few cells; that was all it took.
Then their hearts began to beat like mine,
only faster.
When the genetic antiphon spelled their bodies out,
I became a parent.</font>

passages.name: vulnerable and exhilarated
passages.text:
Water would pool in the woods--depressions on the forest floor--and then freeze in the winter. I would get on my belly in my snowsuit and moon boots and observe the air bubbles trapped underneath the ice, because I thought they were alive, like giant amoeba. I'd press down on the ice. And they were alive, with millions of bacteria in the icy oval. I wiped my nose on my mitten and imagined hoofbeats along the ridge deeper in the woods. When I went too far into the woods by myself I would get scared. It wasn't our land to begin with. Getting caught was in the back of my mind, but I was more unnerved by the silence, the lack of all sounds except for the birches and maples rustling and, further in, the little creek with the sloping banks where the water trickled. The creek that I was never able to find the origin of, and even now when I try to follow its path on Google Maps I get confused as to where it comes and goes. 

[img[splurt-blur][6]

passages.name: Untitled Passage 1
passages.text:
We are cell-clusters of accreted desires. We have receptor points of love and goodwill, where we also intersect with “fellow-feeling.” 

Love in an ecological sense reveals itself as an impersonal force. That is to say, it should be as natural as photosynthesis. It doesn’t need human acclaim to survive. Loving other people should have the simplicity and directness of bandaging a wounded dog’s leg. 

Against the backdrop of quasars, what are poisonous family relations? What are our tribes? 

in the morning I will hear the trucks
go all out

passages.name: css
5b
passages.text:
When I was growing up in Pennsylvania, I would confuse innocence with the anxiety of having that innocence taken away from me. In the deep woods behind our house, I built forts out of fallen trees and branches, building what I considered to be crude replicas of 18th century French forts, on land claimed, during that time, by the French Empire.

I was [[vulnerable and exhilarated]].
<<set $teeth to 1>>

passages.name: 6b
passages.text:
<font color=Crimson><<hoverreplace "->">>(April 2011, Zlin, the Czech Republic)<<endhoverreplace>></font>

<font color=Tan>After the implantation in the clinic, I held my wife's <<replace "hand.">>hand.

We had tried for so long. And it certainly wasn't something that people liked to talk about, politely. For awhile, Facebook became nearly unbearable. The trials and errors. The constant misses.

The hopeless pain, which my wife bore in her bones and ached in a way that I wouldn't understand.

And it made matters a bit skewed when the glimmer of hope did arrive by fluke. When we found out the cheapest best option by far, as Americans, was to fly to Moravia for //in vitro// fertilization.<<endreplace>> 

This was scientific romance.</font>

[[⚗|7a]]

passages.name: glaciers
passages.text:
<font color=CornflowerBlue>
This little lake was right on the edge of the glaciers, carved out during the Wisconsin Glaciation. 

When these glaciers retreated and started to melt about 9,000 years ago,

the sea levels rose and slowly drowned the land thousands of miles away between Britain and the continent: 

Doggerland

Now when the North Sea bottom is dredged, they find:</font> <font color=Crimson><<hoverreplace>>(dredge)<<becomes>><<print either("wooly mammoth tusk, 10 cm.", "petrified wood, 5 cm.", "human jawbone, worn molars","deer femur with ax inflections", "serrated antler arrowhead, 4 cm.", "seaweed strand", "boar skull", "bifacial flint arrowhead", "hagfish, .5 m")>><<endhoverreplace>>
</font>
